Question 1

  1. In the table below, information is given on the presence or absence (denoted by \(1\) and \(0\), respectively) of \(6\) unspecified attributes, denoted A1, …, A6, in Lions, Giraffes, Sheep and Humans. \[ \begin{array}{cccccccc} \textrm{Individual} &&\textrm{A1}&\textrm{A2}&\textrm{A3}&\textrm{A4}&\textrm{A5}&\textrm{A6}\\ &&&&&&\\ \textrm{Lion}&&1&1&0&0&1&1\\ \textrm{Giraffe}&&1&1&1&0&0&1\\ \textrm{Sheep}&&1&0&0&1&0&1\\ \textrm{Human}&&0&0&0&0&1&0 \end{array} \]
  1. Use the information in the table to calculate a similarity matrix based on the simple matching coefficient.
Solution

You should do this by hand, but the answer is

         lion giraffe sheep human
lion    1.000   0.667 0.500 0.500
giraffe 0.667   1.000 0.500 0.167
sheep   0.500   0.500 1.000 0.333
human   0.500   0.167 0.333 1.000
  1. Using a suitable transformation, convert the similarity matrix into a dissimilarity matrix, \(\mathbf D\) say.
Solution

You can do this as we did in the chapter on MDS \[d_{ij}=\left ( f_{ii}+f_{jj} -2f_{ij} \right )^{1/2}\] which gives

         lion giraffe sheep
giraffe 0.816              
sheep   1.000   1.000      
human   1.000   1.290 1.150

You can also just do 1-SMC, but that results in a different distance function.

  1. Apply the single linkage method to the matrix \(\mathbf D\). Summarise your results graphically in a dendrogram.
Solution

The ordering of the distances is given by \[ d_{LG}< d_{LS}=d_{LH} = d_{GS}<d_{SH}<d_{GH}. \]

So the sequence of clusters given by single linkage is

  • Stage 0: clusters are \(\{\text{L}\}\), \(\{\text{G}\}\), \(\{\text{S}\}\) and \(\{\text{H}\}\).

  • Stage 1: qw join the clusters \(\{L\}\) and \(\{G\}\) at distance 0.816 giving new clusters \(\{\text{L}, \text{G}\}\), \(\{\text{S}\}\) and \(\{\text{H}\}\) and new distance matrix is

    LG    S
S 1.00     
H 1.00 1.15
  • Stage 2: we have a tie, so we join LG with S and H (at distance 1.0), giving the clusters \(\{\text{L}, \text{G}, \text{S}, \text{H}\}\).

The dendrogram is as follows

  1. Apply the complete linkage method to the matrix \(\mathbf D\). Summarise your results graphically in a dendrogram.
Solution

The first two stages are the same as for single linkage:

  • Stage \(0^\prime\): clusters are \(\{\text{L}\}\), \(\{\text{G}\}\), \(\{\text{S}\}\) and \(\{\text{H}\}\). and the distance matrix is
         lion giraffe sheep
giraffe 0.816              
sheep   1.000   1.000      
human   1.000   1.290 1.150
  • Stage \(1^\prime\): we join L and G (at distance 0.816), giving clusters \(\{\text{L}, \text{G}\}\), \(\{\text{S}\}\) and \(\{\text{H}\}\). The new distance matrix between clusters is
    LG    S
S 1.00     
H 1.29 1.15

as \[ d^\ast_C(\{L,G\}, \{S\})=\max (d_{LS}, d_{GS})=1, \] \[ d_C^\ast (\{L,G\}, \{H\})=\max (d_{LH},d_{GH})=1.2910 \]

  • Stage \(2^\prime\): we join LG and S at distance 1, giving clusters \(\{\text{L}, \text{G}, \text{S}\}\) and \(\{\text{H}\}\). The new distance matrix is
   LGS
H 1.29

as

\[ d_C^\ast (\{LGH\}, \{S\})=\max (1.29, 1.15)=1.29. \]

  • Stage \(3^\prime\): we join the final \(\{LGH\}\) and \(\{S\}\) at distance 1.29, giving cluster \(\{\text{L}, \text{G}, \text{S}, \text{H}\}\).

  1. Suppose exactly two clusters are required. What would be your clusters based on single linkage and complete linkage?
Solution

If we settle on precisely two clusters then complete linkage suggests \(\{\)L,G,S\(\}\) and \(\{\)H\(\}\). Single linkage cannot be used to create two clusters without a tie-breaking rule.

  1. Repeat part v., but this time with three clusters rather than two.
Solution

If we decide on three clusters, both single linkage and complete linkage suggest the following three clusters: \(\{\)L,G\(\}\), \(\{\)S\(\}\) and \(\{\)H\(\}\).

  1. Briefly (i.e. in one or two sentences) summarise your findings.
Solution

In this example the single linkage and complete linkage approaches give similar (but not identical) results.

Question 2

Attempt question 4b from the 2017-18 exam paper.

Solution
  1. Hierarchical clustering methods work by creating a hierarchy of clusters, in which clusters at each level of the heirarchy are formed by merging or splitting clusters from a neighbouring level of the hierarchy.

  • agglomerative clustering methods start with the finest partition (one observation per cluster) and progressively combine clusters.

  • divisive/splitting clustering methods start with a single cluster, and then progressively splits or divides clusters.

  1. We’ll go through the calculation by hand during the lecture.
D.sl <-hclust(dist(dat[,1:2])^2, method="single")
plot(D.sl)

cutree(D.sl,h = 0.3)
[1] 1 1 1 1 2 1

So at threshold 0.3 we have clusteres \(\{1,2,3,4,6\}\) and \(\{5\}\).

D.sl <-hclust(dist(dat[,1:2])^2, method="complete")
plot(D.sl)

cutree(D.sl,h = 0.75)
[1] 1 2 1 2 2 1

At threshold 0.6 we get clusters \(\{1,3,6\}\) and \(\{2,4,5\}\).

Question 3

Prove Equation 9.2, namely that the within-cluster scatter reduces to \[\begin{align} W(\delta) &= \frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^K \sum_{i: \delta(i)=k} \sum_{i': \delta(i')=k} ||\mathbf x_i - \mathbf x_{i'}||_2^2 \\ &= \sum_{k=1}^K n_k \sum_{i: \delta(i)=k} ||\mathbf x_{i} - \hat{{\boldsymbol{\mu}}}_k||_2^2 \end{align}\]

Solution

To prove this we just need to show that for \(\mathbf x_1, \ldots, \mathbf x_n\) we have

\[\sum_{i}\sum_{j} ||\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j||^2=2n \sum_i ||\mathbf x_i- \hat{\mu}||^2\]

Starting with the LHS \[\begin{align*} \sum_{i}\sum_{j} ||\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j||^2&=\sum_{i}\sum_{j} ||(\mathbf x_i-\hat{\mu}) + (\hat{\mu}-\mathbf x_j)||^2\\ &=\sum_{i}\sum_{j} ||\mathbf x_i - \hat{\mu}||^2 -2(\mathbf x_i - \hat{\mu})^\top (\mathbf x_j - \hat{\mu}) + ||\mathbf x_j - \hat{\mu}||^2\\ &=2n\sum_{i} ||\mathbf x_i - \hat{\mu}||^2 \end{align*}\] as required.
